1️⃣ Functions (Reuse Logic Like a Pro)
Simple Idea

👉 A function is a reusable block of code

Real-World Example

Think of a machine in a factory:

Input → Machine → Output

You don’t rebuild the machine every time.
You just reuse it.

C++ Example
int add(int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
}

int main()
{
    int result = add(3, 4);
    cout << result;
}
What Actually Happens
You call:
add(3, 4);
Control goes to function:
a = 3, b = 4
It returns:
7
Stored in result
Mental Model (Never Forget)
Function = Machine
Input → Process → Output
Why Functions Exist

Without function:

cout << 3 + 4;
cout << 5 + 6;

Repeating logic ❌

With function:

add(3,4);
add(5,6);

Reusable ✅

Types of Functions
Type	Meaning
With return	gives output
Without return	just performs task
Example (No Return)
void greet()
{
    cout << "Hello";
}
Connection to What You Know

In real life:

Calculator → reusable tool

👉 Function = your custom calculator

Common Mistake 🔥
int add(int a, int b)
{
    cout << a + b;  // ❌ not returning
}

👉 Should use return

How to Remember

Ask:

“Am I repeating logic?”

👉 If YES → use function

2️⃣ Arrays (Store Multiple Values)
Simple Idea

👉 Array = collection of same type data stored together

Real-World Example

Think of:

Roll numbers of students

Instead of:

int r1 = 10;
int r2 = 20;
int r3 = 30;

We use:

int arr[3] = {10, 20, 30};
What Happens Internally

Memory looks like:

arr[0] → 10  
arr[1] → 20  
arr[2] → 30  

👉 Stored continuously in memory

Mental Model
Array = Line of boxes (same type)
Accessing Elements
cout << arr[0];  // 10

👉 Index starts from 0

Why Arrays Matter

Without array:

marks1, marks2, marks3...

Messy ❌

With array:

marks[0], marks[1], marks[2]

Organized ✅

Loop + Array (POWER COMBO 🔥)
int arr[3] = {10, 20, 30};

for(int i=0; i<3; i++)
{
    cout << arr[i];
}
Connection to What You Know

In real life:

Books in a shelf → arranged in order

👉 Array = structured storage

Common Mistake 🔥
int arr[3] = {10,20,30};
cout << arr[3];  // ❌ out of bounds

👉 Valid index: 0 to 2

How to Remember
Array index always starts from 0

Think:

First element = 0th position
